===============================================================================
K2N: KNOTTED TO NESTED STANDALONE PACKAGE
===============================================================================
Written by: Sandra Smit (S.Smit@few.vu.nl)
Last updated on: 18 Oct 2007

This package contains stripped down versions of the full source code
available as part of the PyCogent project:
http://sourceforge.net/projects/pycogent/

If you use this code in your work, please cite:

Sandra Smit, Kristian Rother, Jaap Heringa, and Rob Knight.
From knotted to nested RNA structures: a variety of computational methods
for pseudoknot removal. (2007) Submitted.

===============================================================================
CODE AND EXAMPLE DATA
===============================================================================

Script to control pseudoknot removal methods:
knotted2nested.py

Related scripts:
knots.py -- Module with pseudoknot removal methods
bpseq.py -- Parser for bpseq format
ct_simple.py -- Parser for ct format
output.py -- Routines to produce output
rna2d.py -- module with RNA structure representations
dict2d.py -- module with 2D dictionary

example_data contains several data files that can be used for testing

===============================================================================
INSTALLATION
===============================================================================

This package requires the following packages to be installed:
python (2.3 or higher)
numpy (1.0.1 or higher)

===============================================================================
USAGE
===============================================================================

Use "python knotted2nested.py -h" for help

General usage:
python knotted2nested.py [options] <input file>

Examples:
python knotted2nested.py -f bpseq -F vienna -m OA -o BPS 
    example_data/example_small.bpseq
python knotted2nested.py -f ct -F bpseq -m IO example_data/example_large.ct 

===============================================================================
DOCUMENTATION
===============================================================================

See knotted2nested.py, the web interface (at www.ibi.vu.nl/programs/k2nwww),
and the paper for a description of the methods.

